    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Tufted, low shrub forming clumps of numerous, upright, white-woolly stems bearing alternate paddle-shaped leaves which point upwards and are densely-felted on both surfaces. Flowers borne is crowded, flat-topped clusters at the tips of the stems. Bracts of flowers with spreading papery-white tips.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_10266",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Stems typically about 50 cm tall. Flowerheads about 16 mm in diameter.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_10267",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Broad coastal band from about Clanwilliam in the north to Bredasdorp in the east.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_10268",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Found on coastal dunes and deep coastal sands, but also inland on sandstone slopes. Extends almost down to high water mark on sandy shores (as depicted). Pollinated by insects.</p><p>The attractive, silvery foliage and long-lasting flowers make this a popular border plant in coastal gardens or as a pot plant.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_10269",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_10270",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers August to November. The outer florets in each head are female and the central florets male.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_10271",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The only species in the genus but can be confused with other papery flowers in genera such as <i>Helichrysum</i>.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_10272",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Manning, J (2007). Field Guide to Fynbos. Cape Town: Random House Struik. (p. 384).<br><br>Manning, J & Goldblatt, P (2000). South African Wild Flower Guide 7: West Coast. Botanical Society of South Africa (p. 198).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_10273",
